{{Taxobox | image = Rhinopoma microphyllum.jpg | status = LC | status_system = IUCN3.1 | status_ref=<ref name="iucn 2017">{{cite journal| last1=Monadjem| first1= A.| last2= Palmeirim| first2= J.| last3= Aulagnier| first3= S.| year= 2017| title= Rhinopoma microphyllum| journal= The IUCN Red List of Threatened Species| volume= 2017| page= e.T19600A21998943| url= https://dx.doi.org/10.2305/IUCN.UK.2017-2.RLTS.T19600A21998943.en}}</ref> | regnum = [[Animalia]] | phylum = [[Chordata]] | classis = [[Mammalia]] | ordo = [[Chiroptera]] | familia = [[Rhinopomatidae]] | genus = ''[[Rhinopoma]]'' | species = '''''R. microphyllum''''' | binomial = ''Rhinopoma microphyllum'' | binomial_authority = ([[Morten Thrane Brünnich|Brünnich]], 1792) | synonyms = | range_map = Greater Mouse-tailed Bat area.png | range_map_caption = Greater mouse-tailed bat range }}
The '''greater mouse-tailed bat''' (''Rhinopoma microphyllum'') is a species of [[bat]] in the [[Rhinopomatidae]] family.<ref>Schlitter, Duane A., and Mazin B. Qumsiyeh. "[https://academic.oup.com/mspecies/article-pdf/doi/10.2307/3504243/8071428/542-1.pdf Rhinopoma microphyllum]." Mammalian Species 542 (1996): 1-5.</ref> It is found in [[Algeria]], [[Bangladesh]], [[Burkina Faso]], the [[Central African Republic]], [[Chad]], [[Djibouti]], [[Egypt]], [[Eritrea]], [[Ethiopia]], [[India]], [[Indonesia]], [[Iran]], [[Israel]], [[Iraq]], [[Jordan]], [[Libya]], [[Mali]], [[Mauritania]], [[Morocco]], [[Myanmar]], [[Niger]], [[Nigeria]], [[Oman]], [[Pakistan]], [[Saudi Arabia]], [[Senegal]], [[Sudan]], [[Thailand]], [[Tunisia]], the [[Western Sahara]] and [[Yemen]]. Its natural [[habitat]] is subtropical or tropical dry [[shrubland]]. They mate at the beginning of spring.
According to a recent research published in [[Royal Society of London]], the species Rhinopoma microphyllum is found to be hibernating at the unusually warm and constant temperature of 68&nbsp;°F in caves in Israel's [[Jordan Rift Valley|Great Rift Valley]]. From October to February, these bats were discovered semi-conscious, breathing only once every 15–30 minutes, with extremely low energy expenditures.<ref>{{cite journal | url=http://www.sciguru.org/newsitem/18645/bat-species-first-mammal-found-hibernating-constant-warm-temperatures | title=Subtropical mouse-tailed bats use geothermally heated caves for winter hibernation |author1=Eran Levin |author2=Brit Plotnik |author3=Eran Amichai |author4=Luzie J. Braulke |author5=Shmulik Landau |author6=Yoram Yom-Tov |author7=Noga Kronfeld-Schor | journal=Royal Society of London |date=April 2015 | volume=282 | issue=1804 | doi=10.1098/rspb.2014.2781|pmc=4375864 }}</ref>
