[[File:Kgotla_(Gathering_place)_at_the_Domboshaba_ruins_(Domboshaba_cultural_festival_2017).jpg|thumb|left|Public meeting place or Kgotla.([[Botswana]])]]
A '''''kgotla''''' {{IPAc-en|ˈ|k|oʊ|t|.|l|ə}} is a public meeting, community council or [[customary law|traditional law]] court of a [[Botswana]] village. It is usually headed by the village [[Tribal chief|chief]] or headman, and community decisions are always arrived at by [[consensus]]. Anyone at all is allowed to speak, and no one may interrupt while someone is "having their say". In fact there is a [[Setswana]] saying that the highest form of war is dialogue (''[[ntwa kgolo ke ya molomo]]''). Because of this tradition, Botswana claims to be one of the world's oldest [[democracy|democracies]].{{cn| date= October 2017}}

The custom of allowing everyone their full say is carried over into meetings of all kinds, from discussing a bill to a staff briefing, and can mean meetings last many hours.{{cn| date= October 2017}}

''Kgotla'' can also refer to the place where such meetings are held. This can range from a few chairs under a shade canopy to a permanent ground with covered seating. In both senses, the term is a [[loan word]] in Botswana English from [[Setswana]], where it means ''court''.{{cn| date= October 2017}}

In [[South African English]], a '''''lekgotla''''' is a meeting called by government to discuss strategy planning. The term is still a loan word from [[Setswana language|Setswana]], again meaning ''court''.{{cn| date= October 2017}}

